The compile keyword has two arguments: A name of an expression to be compiled. A set of compilation rules using the format (backend → string) where the string is the text we inline. This is an example: $ cat tests/positive/HelloWorld
...
axiom Action : Type;
compile Action { ghc ↦ "IO ()";
};
... The following Juvix examples are NOT valid. One can not repeat backend inside a compile block. ...
axiom Action : Type;
compile Action { ghc ↦ "IO ()"; ghc ↦ "IO ()"; --
};
... One name, one compile block, no more. ...
axiom Action : Type;
compile Action { ghc ↦ "IO ()";
};
compile Action { ghc ↦ "IO ()";
};
... A compile block must be in the same module as their name definition. $ cat A.mjuvix
...
axiom Action : Type;
... $ cat B.mjuvix
...
compile Action { ghc ↦ "IO ()";
};
